In pre-modern [[medicine]], the term '''catagmatic''' generally referred to any treatment purported to heal [[bone fracture]]s, by promoting the formation of a [[callus]].

The principal catagmatics were [[Armenian bole]], [[gum tragacanth]], [[osteocolla]], [[Cyprus]] nuts, [[frankincense]], [[aloe]]s, and [[acacia]].

The word comes from the Greek ''καταγμα'', "fracture".
