{{unreferenced|date=August 2015}}
A '''dimorphic root system''' is a plant [[root]] system with two distinct root forms, which are adapted to perform different functions. One of the most common manifestations is in plants with both a [[taproot]], which grows straight down to the water table, from which it obtains water for the plant; and a system of [[lateral root]]s, which obtain [[minerals]].

[[Category:Plant roots]]


{{botany-stub}}

{{Unreferenced|date=December 2008}}
In [[chromatography]], '''endcapping''' refers to the replacement of accessible [[silanol]] groups in a bonded [[Stationary phase (chemistry)|stationary phase]] by [[trimethylsilyl]] groups.

Endcapping technology prevents the tailing of a [[Polarity (chemistry)|polar]] [[Chemical compound|compound]]'s peak and shows very high durability even with an [[alkaline]] [[mobile phase]] because of the strong film covering the stationary phase surface.

