[[ File:José Arechavaleta.jpg|right|thumb|José Arechavaleta (1838–1912)]] '''José Arechavaleta''' (27 September 1838, Urioste, near [[Bilbao]] – 16 June 1912, [[Montevideo]]) was a Spanish-born [[pharmacist]], [[geologist]] and [[naturalist]], active in Uruguay.
At the age of 18, he emigrated to [[Uruguay]], where he made the acquaintanceship of [[botanist]] José Ernesto Gibert (1818–1886). In 1862 he obtained a degree in pharmacy, and later taught classes in botany, [[zoology]] and [[natural history]] at the [[University of the Republic (Uruguay)|University of the Republic]] in [[Montevideo]]. In 1892 he was appointed general director of the natural history museum in Montevideo, a position he kept until his death in 1912.<ref name=JS>[http://plants.jstor.org/person/bm000000234 JSTOR Global Plants] biography</ref><ref>[http://www.mec.gub.uy/munhina/biograf2.htm Biografías - MNHNA] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120729044436/http://www.mec.gub.uy/munhina/biograf2.htm |date=2012-07-29 }} biographical information</ref>
In Uruguay, he studied and collected insects from all parts of the country, being particularly interested in [[Coleoptera]]. As a botanist, he published a major work on [[Poaceae|grasses]] native to the country. He is credited with establishing [[bacteriology]] laboratories at the University Institute of Experimental Hygiene.<ref name=JS/> In 1899 the plant genus ''[[ Arechavaletaia]]'' was named in his honor by [[Carlos Luigi Spegazzini]].<ref>[https://www.gbif.org/species/101513685 GBIF] Arechavaletaia</ref>
== Principal works == * ''Las gramíneas uruguayas'', 1894 - [[Gramineae]] of Uruguay. * ''Flora uruguaya; enumeración y descripción breve de las plantas conocidas hasta hoy y de algunas nuevas que nacen espontaneamente y viven en la República Uruguaya'', 1901 - Uruguayan flora, list and brief description of the plants known in the Uruguayan Republic.<ref>[https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/creator/7197#/titles Biodiversity Heritage Library] publications</ref> == Honors == Some botanical species were named in Arechavaleta's honor: * ([[Arecaceae]]) ''[[Cocos arechavaletana]]'' <small>[[Barb.Rodr.]]</small><ref>Contr. Jard. Bot. Rio de Janeiro i. 43 (IK)</ref> * ([[Malvaceae]]) ''[[Pavonia arechavaletana]]'' <small>[[Krapov.]] & [[Paul Fryxell|Fryxell]]</small><ref>Bonplandia (Corrientes) 19(1): 81 2010</ref>
